 Somerset, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Orchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["topographic or occupational name from residence near (or perhaps employment at) an orchard, Middle English <i>orchard</i> (Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i>).","habitational name from any of the places called Orchard. Those in Devon and Somerset are named from Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i> (a compound of <i>wort</i>, <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant’ (later associated with Latin <i>hortus</i> ‘garden’) + <i>geard</i> ‘yard, enclosure’), while East and West Orchard near Shaftesbury in Dorset derive from Primitive Welsh <i>ar</i> ‘beside, in front of, facing’ + <i>ced</i> ‘wood’.","rare variant of Scottish   Urquhart  . Compare   Orahood  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Urquhart","meanings":["Scottish (Ross and Cromarty): habitational name from any of various places in Scotland so called, notably the barony of Urquhart (Inverness), or places in Ross and Cromarty, Morayshire, and Fife. All are thought to derive from Pictish <i>ar</i> ‘on, by’ + Pictish <i>carden</i> ‘enclosure’ or ‘wood, copse’. Some bearers of this name trace their descent from William <i>de Urchard</i>, who fought for Robert the Bruce between 1297 and 1328."]},{"name":"Orahood","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Orchard   3, itself a rare English variant of Scottish   Urquhart  .","History: The Orahoods can trace their origin to Alexander, Joshua, and Thomas Orahood, who in the second half of the 18th century lived in VA and are believed to come to America from Scotland. Their surname is also listed in the forms <i>Orrahud</i>, <i>Arahood</i>, <i>Arrowhood</i>, and <i>Orchard</i>, the last one being the most likely original form."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":36,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Orchard was born in 1346, in Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, his father, Thomas de Orchard, was 16 and his mother, Alice of England, was 21. He married Margaret Manningford in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1410, in Somerset, England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1346–1410":"1346–1410","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1330–1397":"1330–1397","1326–1380":"1326–1380","1330":"1330","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1326":"1326","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1397":"1397","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1419":"1419","Holway Manor, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Taunton Manor, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Taunton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1346–1410":"1346–1410","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1330–1397":"1330–1397","1326–1380":"1326–1380","1330":"1330","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1326":"1326","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1397":"1397","Abt 1380":"noin 1380","1419":"1419","Holway Manor, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Taunton Manor, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Taunton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","